    },
    {
      "id": "704c0dbfa012b641d0cf885e7ff0bd704c8a1154",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-04-18 00:09:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nit's not clear why do we need linkea on .lustre at all, it's not supposed to be a parent for any user-created file/directory ?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "666fb44a2f81d163aab2654661c9d743a00cbd2d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-04-18 00:34:38.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "dd9d500e73e73bfb27f536dbb262ae01658f8465",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-04-18 00:43:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.4/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/050b0236-a7bd-11e2-b3cc-52540035b04c).  Ran 14 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "90fe2e747cccd96d1d9a4e38ed0cd0c6cc5e88a5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-04-18 00:47:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> it's not clear why do we need linkea on .lustre at all, it's not supposed to be a parent for any user-created file/directory ?\n\nWhen LFSCK scans the /ROOT, it will found \".lustre\" has no linkEA, then it is misguided that the system is \"inconsistent\" status and try to fix it. In fact, it is only the \".lustre\" has no linkEA, it is not worth for the LFSCK to distinguish such special case during the whole system directories scanning.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a08ee3437dc6749a6bb7b575a95a8c6fd24f1f2a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-04-18 00:50:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> When LFSCK scans the /ROOT, it will found \".lustre\" has no linkEA, then it is misguided that the system is \"inconsistent\" status and try to fix it. In fact, it is only the \".lustre\" has no linkEA, it is not worth for the LFSCK to distinguish such special case during the whole system directories scanning.\n\nbut similarly you bring special code to MDD now.. couldn't we instead create it with mdd_create() *directly* (not via ->prepare() or something like that).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "376b130bb6a8cabfb3303dd68660f5232fa53e06",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-04-18 01:46:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> but similarly you bring special code to MDD now.. couldn't we instead create it with mdd_create() *directly* (not via ->prepare() or something like that).\n\nSome confused.. You mean mdd_create() for the \".lustre\" together with its linkEA directly? We originally did that, but it has been chanced when the patch for creating local file via local APIs landed. Would you please to explain in detail how to?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3962f51f86412df969bbc9244784edf3069f4242",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2013-04-18 04:14:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nthe main intent of that patch was to get rid of bottom-to-up ->prepare() callchain which doesn't work with OST stack and llo* things.. I'll check with Mike.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3c93c914597a45979b9d7492fcd7f0bb8f8ef05c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2013-04-21 15:59:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI found that also a bit wrong, you are saying that it is not good to add exception in lfsck checks but you think it is OK to add more complex code in Lustre itself, note, lfsck is tool for Lustre but not otherwise. IMO, lfsck should know that .lustre is special and handle it, I don't see any problem here.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "46d43403dabbc91435085a2e50aa4fa27e9996d9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-04-22 00:41:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nLFSCK can know that \".lustre\" is special and can process it specially. But consider performance, I do NOT think it is worth to distinguish the \".lustre\" from all the other normal files/directories.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e38b9976b8df2e97e912c00ab11d60dd75ea45d5",
      "author": {
